        "text": "Henry Corbin spent a lifetime translating the lost organs of Western perception. Not inventing them — finding them already articulated in the texts of Suhrawardi, Ibn Arabi, Mulla Sadra Shirazi, and the Sufi masters of Iran. What he recovered was not a doctrine but an organ: the active Imagination, a cognitive faculty with its own noetic dignity, and the world it perceives, the mundus imaginalis. This is not fantasy, not myth in the debased sense, not 'imaginary' as we use the word to mean unreal. It is an intermediate ontological region, as real as matter and as real as spirit, and the soul must be trained to see it."
