        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "The ladder: One, Intellect, Soul, celestial forms, lower forms, material reception. De vita III.2 describes the harmony of the world and human nature according to the stars. The cosmos is not dead space. It is aliving order. De vita III.3 gives the three-level structure that makes this order coherent: \"World-soul animates all things. World-body receives form. World-spirit mediates between soul and body. Human spirit can receive world-spirit.\" De vita III.4 describes absorbing world-spirit through the Sun and Jupiter — reception, not domination. De vita III.5 presents the welcoming triad: \"Jupiter, Sun, and Venus are the three Graces. They give life, temperance, beauty, joy, and expansion.\" The passage that follows, from later in Book III, is the bridge between Book I'sphysiology and Book III'scosmology. Ficino writes: \"Our spiritus is in conformity with the rays of the heavenly spiritus, which penetrates everything either secretly or obviously. It shows afar greater kinship when we have astrong desire for that life and are seeking abenefit that is consistent with it, and thus transfer our own spiritus into its rays by means of love, particularly if we make use of song and light and the perfume appropriate to the deity, like the hymns that Orpheus consecrated to the cosmic deities.\" Similiter spiritus noster radiis illius tam occultis, quam manifestis omnia penetrantibus. Evadit etiam longe cognatior, quando erga vitam illam vehementer afficimur consentaneum illi beneficium exoptantes, atque ita spiritum nostrum in illius radios transferentes amore praesertim si cantum et lumen adhibemus, odoremque numini consentaneum quales Orpheus hymnos mundanis numinibus consecravit. The same vapour that connects soul and body within the human being connects the human being to the cosmos. The spirits are conformable. Through desire, love, song, light, and perfume, the human spirit transfers itself into the celestial rays. The remaining chapters of Book III'sopening section map this cosmic medicine onto the physiological architecture of Book I. De vita III.6 returns to the natural, vital, and animal powers — the same three forces that conceive, nourish, and sustain the spirits in the human body — now in astrological key. De vita III.7 presents the Moon as the mediator: closest to Earth, linked to bodily change, timing, growth, moisture, and medical application. De vita III.8 adds that fixed stars matter as specific powers; the celestial influence is not limited to the seven planets. De vita III.9 addresses planetary dignities, which affect medical timing — planets work differently depending on their condition. De vita III.10 concludes this section with the practical application: medicines must be prepared under the right celestial conditions. ## IV. The Celestial Medicine De vita III.11 — \"World-soul spreads its force through quintessence as spirit inside the World's Body, especially into things that absorb more of that spirit. Things filled with purer spirit include wine, sugar, balsam, gold, precious stones, sweet smells, shining things, and hot, moist, clear, subtle substances.\""
