        "text": "De vita III.12 extends the principle to human making: \"Not only natural objects but artificial things can receive occult powers from stars.\" This one sentence prepares the entire talismanic art. The human-made object is not outside the system of correspondences. De vita III.14 presents the most vivid catalogue in the entire work: \"Solar things include heliotrope, gold, golden colours, chrysolite, carbuncle, myrrh, frankincense, musk, amber, balsam, yellow honey, saffron, cinnamon. Solar animals include the ram, hawk, cock, swan, lion, scarab, and crocodile. There are also solar human types and solar-looking people.\" The catalogue includes metals, gems, plants, scents, foods, animals, human appearances, practices, habits, light, thought, and love. \"Jovial things include silver, jacinth, topaz, coral, crystal, beryl, sapphire, airy colours, wine, sugar, white honey. Also Jovial thoughts, feelings, and company with Jovial people.\" To become solar, one uses not only solar objects but solar perception, solar thought, solar love, solar habits. Celestial influence is social and affective. Company matters. Feeling matters. De vita III.15 makes aclaim that ties Book III back to Books Iand II: \"Medicines are stronger than images because they enter the body more directly.\" Book Igave remedies. Book II gave longevity substances. Book III reveals them as part of acosmic ecology. The next group of chapters — De vita III.16 through III.20 — describes the mechanics of the talismanic image. De vita III.16 establishes the principle: \"Heavenly rays do not merely signify. They emit, transmit, and impress power.\" Radiis... vim habere mirabilem. De vita III.17 traces this power to its source: \"The World-soul constructs figures in the heavens and impresses properties on them. Zodiacal images, faces, degrees, images outside the zodiac. The right figure below corresponds to afigure above.\" De vita III.18 describes how the image is engraved — under specific celestial conditions, on specific materials, for specific purposes. De vita III.19 presents the figure of the universe, the image as amodel of the whole, aconfigured microcosm that receives macrocosmic order. De vita III.20 describes the reciprocal relationship between image and spirit: \"Images act on spirit through the subtle medium linking perception, body, and celestial influence. Spirit acts on images in return. The relationship is reciprocal. The operator'semotional state matters: affect, intention, confidence, fear, joy, devotion, or disturbance alter the work.\" De vita III.21 and III.22 extend the same principle to sound. Ficino writes: \"The first music takes place in reason, the second in fantasy, and the third in words. Thence follows song, and after that the movement of the fingers in sound. Lastly the movement of the whole body in gymnastics or dancing. Thus the music of the soul is led by steps to all the limbs of the body.\" The same principle applies to sound as to images. Both work through the spiritus. Both require the engagement of the imaginative faculty. In his letter to Canigiani, quoted in this section, Ficino describes the mechanism:"
