      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Quolibet septennio corpus magnam mutationem patitur, quia dominatio a Saturno ad Lunam redit. Vita naturalis propius aut longius moveri potest per stellas et res materiales. Time is not empty duration. It is patterned by planetary sequence. The body changes according to temporal rulership. Each seventh year, rulership returns from Saturn to the Moon, and the body undergoes amajor transition. Old age is not agradual decline but aseries of thresholds, each one adanger and an opportunity. But Ficino is not afatalist. The stars threaten and promise, but medicine and prudence can intervene. The same passage that describes the septenary dangers also affirms that natural lifespan can be moved. The art of the physician and the art of the astrologer work together to navigate the rhythmic dangers of time. Fatum non est. Stellae minantur et promittunt, sed medicina et prudentia intervenire possunt. The septenary years are the moment where Book II reveals its deepest connection to Book III. The same planets that structure the years of alife also structure the practice of celestial medicine. The seven-year cycles that the aging body undergoes are the same cycles that the astrologer reads to determine the right time for treatment. Book II'sconcern with time prepares the reader for Book III'sconcern with timing. Septenarii anni sunt nexus inter II et III. Iidem planetae qui annos vitae struunt etiam medicinam coelestem regunt. There is no fate. The stars threaten and promise, but medicine and prudence can intervene. Book II is the book of the middle — between repair and opening, between the body and the stars, between time and eternity. It is the least glamorous of the three books, but it is the one without which the others would be incomplete. The instrument must last long enough for the journey. Book II shows how. The reader who completes Book II with care will arrive at Book III prepared. The body has been repaired. The life has been preserved. The stars have been consulted. The time has come for the opening. Corpus reparatum est. Vita conservata est. Stellae consultae sunt. Tempus aperiendi venit. The opening is Book III. But the readiness for it is Book II. Sine libro secundo, liber tertius impossibilis esset. Vita brevis non potest capere coelum. Without Book II, Book III would be impossible. Ashort life cannot receive the heavens. The flame that goes out before its work is done leaves the work undone, and the truth that would have been known through that work remains unknown. The preservation of life is the bridge between the repair of the instrument and its celestial opening. Without that bridge, the ascent collapses. Book II is the unsung hero of the Liber de vita — the book that makes the other two possible. The scholar who ignores it will not live long enough to need Book III. The scholar who embraces it will find the stars waiting. There is no fate. The stars threaten and promise, but medicine and prudence can intervene. Book II argues that longevity is intellectual infrastructure. The scholar must be preserved through time because wisdom takes time. Without Book II, the ascent from repair to celestial reception would lack its middle term. The instrument must last long enough for the journey. Longaevitas est infrastructura intellectualis. Sapiens conservari debet quia sapientia tempus requirit. Ficino'sown life illustrates the principles of Book II. He lived to be sixty-six — old for his time — and produced an enormous body of work: translations of Plato, Plotinus, and the Hermetica; philosophical treatises; medical works; commentaries; hundreds of letters. He could not have done this without the care he took to preserve his own life. The Liber de vita is not theoretical. It is the record of practices that Ficino developed and tested on himself. Ficinus ipse exemplum est. Sexaginta sex annos vixit. Opera ingentia produxit. Liber de vita non est theoricus sed practicus. The preservation of life is not an end in itself. It serves the same goal that Book Iserved — the perfection of the instrument of knowing. Book Irepaired the instrument. Book II keeps it functioning. Book III opens it to the cosmos. Each stage depends on the one before it, and all three serve the same purpose: the realisation of the soul'spotential through the care of the body that carries it. Reparatio, conservatio, apertio. Tria stadia, unus finis: animae perfectio per corporis curam. Book II is the least dramatic of the three books. It contains no talismans, no planetary songs, no Orphic hymns. It is about digestion, diet, dwelling, and the slow work of staying alive. But without it, the drama of Book III would be impossible. The preserved life is the life that can be opened to the stars. The flame that burns steadily is the flame that can receive the light of the heavens. Liber secundus est minimus dramatis sed maximus fundamenti. Vita conservata est vita aperienda. Flamma stabilis est flamma quae lumen coeleste recipere potest. Sine libro secundo, liber tertius impossibilis esset. Vita brevis non potest capere coelum. Without Book II, Book III would be impossible. Ashort life cannot receive the heavens. The flame that goes out before its work is done leaves the work undone, and the truth that would have been known through that work remains unknown. Book II is the unsung hero of the Liber de vita — the book that makes the other two possible."
      }
