        "text": "The structure is astaged ascent. Book Iaddresses the health of scholars. Book II extends life through time. Book III opens the preserved human being to celestial influence. But the shock is that the ascent begins not with metaphysics or theology, but with headaches, digestion, sleep, and medicine. Why does a Platonist write amedical manual? The reader who opens the Liber de vita expecting the author of the Theologia Platonica — the great work on the immortality of the soul — is surprised to find chapters on phlegm, diet, and the best hour for study. The surprise is the point. Ficino is not abandoning Platonism. He is insisting that Platonism must be practical — that the soul cannot ascend to the contemplation of divine things if the body through which it operates is damaged by the very act of study. Platonismus practicus. Non satis est animam immortalem esse docere; opus est corpus instruere quo anima utitur. Practical Platonism. It is not enough to teach that the soul is immortal; the body that the soul uses must be equipped. De vita I.1 gives the first answer. Ficino places the scholar within atriple ecology of support:"
