        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "The mental act has abodily cost. Philosophy is dangerous because it succeeds too well. The mind turns toward incorporeal truth, and the body pays the price. The body becomes half-alive. This is not ametaphor. It is aphysiological description of what happens when the spirit that connects soul and body is depleted by the effort of abstraction. De vita I.7 names the enemies that attack the instrument daily: phlegm, black bile, sexual intercourse, gluttony, and morning sleep. Each clouds, thickens, or misdirects the forces needed for study. Quinque hostes studiosorum: pituita, atra bilis, coitus, gula, somnus matutinus. De vita I.11 traces the deepest connection: \"Since blood comes from digestion, and spirit from blood, and sense from spirit, and reason from sense — the stomach indirectly supports reason.\" The stomach is not beneath the mind. It feeds the medium through which the mind operates. De vita I.12 extends this to the whole body, showing how the natural, vital, and animal powers conceive, nourish, and sustain the spirits. The remaining chapters of Book I — I.13 through I.25 — form acomplete pharmacy for the scholar. Medicines against phlegm, remedies for rheum and headache, care of sight, restoring taste, the special cure of black bile, syrups, pills, liquid medicine, bloodletting, electuaries. For sleeplessness, dullness, and forgetfulness. Pharmacia integra: remedia contra pituitam, rheuma, cephalaeam. Cura visus, gustus, bilis atrae. Syrupi, pilulae, medicinae liquidae, sanguinis missio, electuaria. Each remedy targets alink in the chain from digestion to reason. The pharmacy is not an appendix. It is the practical expression of the theory announced in I.2. De vita I.26 closes Book Iwith ahierarchy that prevents medicine from becoming the whole story:"
