      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Hence only those ‘who\nlive through the Real will never die.’\nIn short, if Ibn al-ʿArabī left behind aliving legacy, it will be\npresent only in the awareness and consciousness of people who\n‘live through the Real.’ Participation in this legacy demands\npassing beyond illusory life and joining with real life."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The many\nthousands of pages that Ibn al-ʿArabī wrote provide ways of\naccessing this life."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Iwant to focus on one way in particular – the\nway that forms the core of the intellectual tradition."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "It is nicely\nexpressed in amaxim cited by Ahmad Samʿānī, agreat teacher\nfrom Persia in the generation before Ibn al-ʿArabī: ‘Recognition\nis the heart’slife with God.’4\nThe heart is the center of human life and consciousness."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The\nQurʾan and the Hadith talk repeatedly about the need to have\nahealthy and wholesome heart, which is an awareness that\nsees things as they truly are and acts appropriately.5 By placing\nawareness and understanding in the heart and not in the brain,\nIslam links up with much of the ancient world."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "This is perhaps\nmost obvious with China, where both Confucians and Daoists\ntell us that the primary human task is to rectify the heart – even\nif most translators render the Chinese word for heart (xin 心) as\n‘mind’ in an attempt to make sense to modern readers.\n3. ʿAttār, Tadhkirat al-awliyāʾ, ed."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Cited in Chittick, Divine Love: Islamic Literature and the Path to God, p. 125.\n5."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "On the central role of the heart in Islamic thought, see Sachiko\nMurata, The Tao of Islam, Chap. 10."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 2 3 In Samʿānī’sterms, achieving ‘the heart’slife with God’ – an\nachievement that Itake as the goal of the intellectual tradition – demands maʿrifa, ‘recognition.’ Scholars like myself typically wafle when translating this word."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In verbal form we use\n‘know’ or ‘recognize,’ and as anoun we translate it as knowledge, science, and, particularly in the context of Suism, gnosis."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The active participle of the word, ʿārif, is typically translated\nas ‘gnostic.’ Another noun from the same root, ʿirfān, which\nin classical texts means exactly the same thing as maʿrifa, has\ncome to be used in recent centuries to designate Suism in its\nmore theoretical forms."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "There are major problems, however, with using the words\ngnosis and gnostic, the least of which is that people associate\nthese words with an ancient Christian heresy."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Adeeper problem is simply that Arabic maʿrifa is an everyday verb and noun,\nwhereas English gnosis is never used in daily conversation –\nexcept perhaps among readers of this journal."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Another problem\ncan be observed in practically all translations of Sui texts available in English."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In discussions of the recognizers – the ‘gnostics’\n– the verbal form of maʿrifa is often used to explain the sort of\nknowing in question, which is to say that the sense of the passage hinges on using the word maʿrifa as averb."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "But English has\nno verb for gnosis, so the speciic characteristics of maʿrifa get\nlost in translation."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Scholars\ntranslate the word variously according to context – knowledge,\nlearning, science."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The distinction between ʿilm and maʿrifa\ncoincides more or less with that between ‘knowing’ and ‘recognizing’ in English.6 ‘Knowing’ is such abasic human experience\nthat it cannot be deined, not least because it is presupposed in\nevery deinition. ‘Recognizing’ is then aspeciic sort of knowing, namely recovering in yourself aknowledge that you already\n6."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Idiscussed the way Ibn al-ʿArabī understands the relationship\nbetween ʿilm and maʿrifa in The Sui Path of Knowledge, pp. 47ff., but in my various translations over the years Ihave\nmade little attempt to distinguish between the two roots (except in the\ncase of ʿārif, ‘gnostic,’ as contrasted with ʿālim, ‘knower,’ or ‘scholar’)."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 Ibn al-ʿArabī William C."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "To speak of recognizing God is to suggest the Qurʾanic\nnotion that knowledge of God pertains to human nature – we\nare born with it but tend to forget it."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The goal of human learning is then to remember and recognize what we have forgotten."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Here the Qurʾanic teaching recalls Plato and his notion of\nanamnesis – the elimination of our amnesia."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Parallels are abundant in ancient texts, such as the teaching of Mencius (6A11)\nthat the goal of life is to recover our lost heart."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "When we look at the use of ʿilm and maʿrifa in Arabic, we\nsee that aclear distinction was commonly drawn between the\ntwo words."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Knowledge that comes from the outside is called\nʿilm – it is the information that we gain from alecture or abook\nor a Google search."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Knowledge that comes from the inside is\ncalled maʿrifa – it is an unmediated knowing, not received from\nany book or teacher."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "It may come to be known because of an outside stimulus,\nbut, once it is found, it is as if the heart has always known it."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In terms of the Islamic creation myth, recognition of the true\nnature of things is latent in the heart because God taught Adam\nthe names when He created him."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In discussions of epistemology, Muslim scholars often called\nknowledge from the outside naqlī, ‘transmitted.’ Those who\ngain airm grounding in this sort of knowledge are then called\nthe ʿulamāʾ, the knowers or scholars."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In contrast, knowledge\nthat is discovered inside the heart was called ʿaqlī, ‘intellectual.’ Those who found intellectual knowledge were commonly\ncalled ʿurafāʾ, ‘recognizers’ – or, as translators usually render\nthe term, ‘gnostics.’ The word recognizer was probably used for\ngreat Sui teachers more often than the word Sui itself, which\nsuggests that Suism was considered the pre-eminent path for\nachieving unmediated knowledge of things as they truly are."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The locus classicus for the intellectual tradition’suse of the\nword maʿrifa is the famous maxim, ‘Whoever recognizes himself recognizes his Lord.’ Most people, including myself, have\ntranslated this as ‘Whoever knows himself knows his Lord.’7\n7."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Ibn al-ʿArabī (and many others) attributes this saying to the Prophet\nand quotes it repeatedly."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Al-Ghazālī says that the saying is by ʿAlī, and Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 4 5 But when we use the word know in this saying and then bring\nup the topic of gnostics, we miss the connection – especially\nwhen the verb ‘recognize’ is used repeatedly in the discussion,\nas is so often the case."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In terms of this saying, the ‘recognizers’ are those who have\nrecognized themselves for who they truly are and, as aconsequence, have recognized the Real for who He truly is."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Once they\nachieve this recognition, they have reached what Samʿānī calls\n‘the heart’slife with God,’ apoint that can be inferred from\nasaying of Abū Yazīd Bastāmī (d.ca.874) often cited by Ibn\nal-ʿArabī: ‘You take your knowledge dead from the dead, but I\ntake my knowledge from the Living who does not die.’    It should be clear that when Isay that Ibn al-ʿArabī is adoorway to the intellectual tradition, Iam using the word intellectual\nin the speciic meaning to which Ihave been alluding, that is,\nintellectual as contrasted with transmitted, or recognized truth\nas contrasted with information."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In order to grasp the signiicance of Ibn al-ʿArabī’sliving legacy, it is important to have a\nclear understanding of the difference between these two sorts\nof knowing."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Transmitted knowledge includes language, history, scripture,\nand everything that we study in schools and universities or learn\nfrom our environment and the media."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In contrast, intellectual\nknowledge must be discovered and recognized within ourselves."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "At the beginning we\nmay receive it from others, but in principle we can discover it\nwithin ourselves; once we ind it, it is self-evident."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In contrast,\nas ageneral rule transmitted knowledge remains hearsay, so it\nnever belongs to us and we can never be sure that it is true."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In short, you cannot acquire intellectual knowledge by\ntransmission, and you cannot discover transmitted knowledge\nwithin yourself."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "When Muslim philosophers discussed the\ndistinction between these two sorts of knowing, it was often\nscholars of the transmitted learning consider this more likely."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 Ibn al-ʿArabī William C."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Chittick because they wanted to distinguish between knowledge transmitted from prophetic revelation and knowledge discovered\nby self-recognition."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "What most people call ‘religion,’ after all,\nis based entirely on transmitted knowledge."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Religion offers\naworldview and amanner of living traced back to adivine\nintervention in history."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "It is worth keeping in mind that in terms of being based on\ntransmitted knowledge, there is no difference between areligious worldview and our own scientiic worldview."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The difference lies rather in the nature of the prophets who set the\nworldviews in motion."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Our own great scientists and thinkers\nmay have made no explicit claim to supra-human sanction, but\ntheir followers see them as true prophets."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Its importance derives from the status of its subject\nmatter, that is, the Real, the only reality that truly is."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The philosophers acknowledged that the object studied in metaphysics\nand the object studied in Kalam (dogmatic theology) were identical."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "But the philosophers held that the Kalam experts were\nhemmed in by their insistence on rooting their knowledge in\nthe transmitted knowledge of scripture, whereas they themselves strove to know the Real without dependence on transmission."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "They did this by disciplining their souls in order to\ngain access to supra-individual intelligence."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Classical Islamic\nphilosophy was nothing if not aspiritual discipline, much in\nthe manner of classical Greek philosophy.8\nIf we look at the overall worldview of the Muslim philosophers, it was not signiicantly different from that of the Kalam\nexperts or the Suis."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "What was different was the language in\nwhich it was posed and the relative degree to which transmitted\nknowledge and intellectual knowledge played roles in its formulation."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "This general worldview was given its most extensive\nand elaborate treatment by Ibn al-ʿArabī."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "One of his great contributions was to show that spiritual practice, moral develop8."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 6 7 ment, ethical foundations, and ritual behavior were all rooted\nin the same Real Being that was understood as the source of\nthe objective universe by the philosophical tradition."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In other\nwords, for him there was no way to justify asharp separation\nbetween ethics and ontology, or subjectivity and objectivity.9\nWhen Muslim scholars set down the Islamic worldview, they\ndid so with the time-honored purpose of explaining the manner in which the One interrelates with the many."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "They typically\ndescribed the descent of all things – their ‘devolution’ if you like\n– from the Real."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "This descent begins with airst manifestation\nthat was called by many names, such as the First Intellect or\nthe Muhammadan Spirit."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "As things move farther from the Real,\nthey are sustained by the Real at every stage of their unfolding."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Eventually everything that emerges from the One reaches a\nfurthest limit, and then it reverses direction and is gradually reintegrated into its origin."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In briefest terms, this worldview held\nthat the One gives rise to the many, the One sustains the many,\nand the One brings the many back to Itself."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In one of\nthe better-known schemes, he describes the entire cosmos as\n‘the Breath of the All-Merciful.’ Each thing in the universe is\naletter, aword, asentence, or abook uttered by God and situated at an appropriate level of deployment within the Breath,\njust as our own spoken words are situated within our breath in\naspeciic manner."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Each created thing is thus aprecise enunciation of the Real Being, and each has its own role to play in the\nbook of creation."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Once the spoken things are deployed in God’s\nBreath, they move back to their origin in aseries of stages."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "This\nprocess might be called an ‘evolution,’ since it reverses the prior\ndevolution and brings about the completion of the great circle\nof being (dāʾirat al-wujūd).10 9."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Itouch on this issue in some detail in ‘Time, Space, and the Objectivity of Ethical Norms’ in Ibn ʿArabī: Heir to the Prophets, Chap. 6.\n10."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "On existence as acircle in Ibn al-ʿArabī’steachings, see Chittick,\nThe Self-Disclosure of God, pp. 220–34."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 Ibn al-ʿArabī 8 William C."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Chittick The ascending ladder back to the One reaches its fullest outward manifestation in human beings, each of which has the\npotential to undertake an inner ascent leading back to the\nFirst Intellect and beyond."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "This ascent is preigured in Islam’s\nsacred history by the Prophet’s miʿrāj, literally, his ‘ladder’– the\nnight journey during which he rose up through the cosmos and\nentered into the presence of God.   It is clear that any worldview depends on transmitted knowledge."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "We think the way we do and believe what we believe\nbecause of what we have received, much of it unconsciously,\nfrom our social and cultural environment."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "We accept certain\ntruths as self-evident not because they are in fact self-evident\nbut because our culture has inculcated away of thinking that\nmakes them appear as self-evident."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Once we step outside of\nour speciic cultural limitations, we see that so-called facts and\ntruths turn out to be situational."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "This statement sounds like\n‘relativism,’ which is sometimes taken as aself-evident truth of\nacademia."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "But for Ibn al-ʿArabī, to speak this way is simply to\nsituate relative, perspectival truth in the context of the Absolute Reality, which in itself allows for no relativism whatsoever."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "To relativize our own supposed certainties is to afirm the most\nbasic of all truths, the only truth that is completely self-evident\nto ahealthy human soul."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "That truth is that there is nothing\ntruly real but the Real, that nothing truly exists but the One\nBeing, or, as the transmitted learning puts it, ‘There is no god\nbut God.’\nIf we keep on believing in what we have received by hearsay\nafter having relected on the fact that it is, after all, hearsay, this\nis no doubt because we trust the source from which we have\nheard it."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Those who subscribe to the religion, they say, need\nto have taqlīd, ‘imitation.’ This is because people must imitate\ntheir teachers in order to gain access to any knowledge, not least\nknowledge of the religion’steachings and scriptures."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In the science of jurisprudence, the word taqlīd has the speciic meaning Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016  9 of following the authority of amujtahid, that is ajurist who is\nsupposed to have achieved acomplete mastery of Islamic law."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Notice, however, that the imitation discussed in jurisprudence pertains only to the Shariʿa – that is, the do’sand the\ndon’ts that the jurists themselves have established on the basis\nof the scriptural sources."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Without such imitation people will\nnot be able to perform Islamic rites and observe the law."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "But\none cannot imitate the jurists or anyone else in the foundational article of faith – that is tawhīd, the assertion that God is\none."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In other words, if one believes in God’sunity in imitation\nof others, that is no better than not believing."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "As the theologians maintain, faith demands acknowledging the truth in the\nheart (al-tasdīq bi’l-qalb), not blind acceptance."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The intellectual\ntradition takes this mindful acknowledgement of tawhīd as the\nirst stage in recognizing the Real."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The Muslim philosophers had no quarrel with the notion that\nreligious guidance is transmitted and that it must be learned\nas such."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "They insisted, however, that intellectual knowledge\ncannot be achieved by way of imitation – it demands aliving\nawareness of its truth."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "No matter what you may have been told\nabout the nature of things by prophets or theologians or scientists, you cannot know the truth or falsity of what they are\nsaying without discovering the reality of things within yourself."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Discovering the truth of things in the heart was commonly\ncalled tahqīq, ‘realization.’ The word is derived from the same\nroot as haqq, which Ihave been translating as Real, but which\nalso means true, correct, appropriate, right, and rightfully due."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Ibn al-ʿArabī frequently points out that the reality of\nagiven thing is the manner in which it participates in the Real\nBeing and makes rightful demands on the subject who knows\nit."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Hence, knowing things as they actually are demands\nrecognizing them in the Real, not outside the Real."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Such recognition will never be found outside ‘the heart’slife with God.’\nIbn al-ʿArabī is usually called a Sui, but he does not apply\nthis word to himself, nor does he often use it to speak of others."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 Ibn al-ʿArabī 10 William C."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Chittick    Western historians are inclined to classify Muslim philosophers\nas rationalists."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In order to make this claim, they need to translate the word ʿaql – intelligence or intellect – as reason."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Unless\nwe are careful about qualifying this translation, we will end up\nsuggesting that ʿaql for Avicenna meant the same as raison for\nDescartes."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "This is to ignore the ontological dimension of intelligence, which is much discussed by the philosophers and central to the Islamic worldview."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Take, for example, the word wujūd, which is used by philosophers and theologians to designate existence or being."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Literally\nit means inding, perceiving, and knowing; it came to mean\nexistence in the usage of the philosophers."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "After all, to exist is\nto be found and perceived (if not by us, certainly by the Real)."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "It follows that recognition, which is intelligence inding the\ntruth and reality of things within itself, is not just the knowing\nawareness of the mind and heart; it is also the very existence of\nthe mind and heart."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Inasmuch as intelligence is identical with\nits source, it is the radiance of God."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "By giving systematic form\nto philo-sophia, ‘the love of wisdom,’ philosophers were striving\n11."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "He uses this expression in al-Nusūs (‘The Texts,’ p. 28; https://\nsbsuny.academia.edu/WilliamCChittick)."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In the Persian part of his correspondence with Nasīr al-Dīn Tūsī, he uses the equivalent expression\nmadhhab-iahl-i tahqīq: Annäherungen (al-Murāsalāt) ed."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 In fact we can just as well call him aphilosopher, or a Kalam\nexpert, or ajurist, except that he is all of these things and none\nof them."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Given the frequency with which he stresses the importance of realization, Ithink one of the few titles that he would\naccept is muhaqqiq, ‘realizer’ – someone who has realized the\ntruth and reality of things by recognizing them in the Real and\nacting in the appropriate manner in the world."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Ibn al-ʿArabī’s\nmost important and inluential disciple – his step-son Sadr\nal-Dīn Qūnawī – refers to their perspective precisely as mashrab\nal-tahqīq, the school of realization.11 11 to discipline their souls and to ind the light of the universal\nintellect inside themselves, thus joining with the ininite light\nof the One Being."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Although he recognized the legitimacy of their pursuits, he\nsaw the human reality as much more extensive than what they\nenvisaged."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "They aimed at union with the First Intellect, but\nhe considered this astunted view of human nature."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "His goal\nwas to open up people to the boundless potential of their own\nselves, made in the image of the Ininite Being."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The\nword Futūhāt means ‘Openings.’ It is often translated as ‘revelations,’ but this suggests that Ibn al-ʿArabī was claiming prophetic status, which is by no means the case."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In fact ‘opening’\nwas awell-established technical term that designates the heart’s\nsudden reception of direct recognition of the Real."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In many passages Ibn al-ʿArabī explains that the heart’sdoor\nwill not be opened unless the seeker has patiently knocked."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Knocking at the door is aprocess that typically takes years and\ncarries no guarantee that the door will be opened, certainly not\nbefore death."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "This means not simply adhering to his external\nSunna, but also climbing the ladder – the miʿrāj – of his inner\nrealization."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The ultimate goal is to achieve the status of the perfect human being (al-insān al-kāmil), who stands in what Ibn\nal-ʿArabī often calls ‘the Muhammadan Station.’ This station\nembraces every possible human perfection, not least the stations\nachieved by the greatest exemplars of human possibility, that\nis, the 124,000 prophets, particularly Adam, Abraham, Moses,\nand Jesus, whom Ibn al-ʿArabī seems to discuss more than any\nof the others."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "As for Muhammad, given that he reached every\npossible human perfection, his station encompassed all the perfections of all the prophets."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Hence the Muhammadan Station is\nthe fullest possible manifestation of divine and human perfection in the universe."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Ibn al-ʿArabī’s Meccan Openings is nothing if not adelineation\nof the multifarious dimensions of the Muhammadan Station."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 Ibn al-ʿArabī William C."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Chittick He wanted to describe these prophetic perfections so that people may aspire to them."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "His great book is a God’s-eye view of all\nthe gates to realization, all the possible ways of coming to be\nwho we are in our deepest selves."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "It is acatalogue of the various\nstandpoints of those who have achieved the life of the heart,\nsummarized under the headings of the book’s 560 chapters –\neven if, as he frequently points out, in discussing any given station he is only alluding to bits and pieces of the vision that it\nbestows on the realizers."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Ibn al-ʿArabī’sstress on the importance of the prophets as the\nsource of guidance in the path of realization cannot be overestimated."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "One of the many places where this can be seen is\nin the manner in which he distances himself from the Muslim philosophers."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Ibegan by saying that philosophers and Suis\nshare the goal of achieving intellectual knowledge."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Both groups\nare striving for knowledge of the Real along with insight into\nhow to put this knowledge into practice."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In other words, both\nphilosophers and Suis set themselves the task of understanding the absolute Haqq, the Real, and learning how to give each\nthing its own relative haqq, its own ‘rightful due.’\nThe philosophers held that they could achieve realization\nby disciplining the soul and actualizing the intellect, but Ibn\nal-ʿArabī criticized them for thinking that they could see the\nfull self-disclosure of the Real with only one eye of the heart,\nthat is the intellect, which quickly perceives God’snecessity\nand transcendence."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Only this eye can perceive the reality of God’s\nimmanence and presence in all things."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The role of the prophets\nis to provide the means to open both eyes and to see the Real\nwith abalanced vision of transcendence and immanence."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Reliance on intellect alone, which understands transcendence but\nfalls short in grasping immanence, prevents full realization of\nthe human potential."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Thus Ibn al-ʿArabī criticized the Muslim\nphilosophers, even while acknowledging that they were correct\nin their vision of the Necessary Existent."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In Chapter 167 of the Meccan Openings, Ibn al-ʿArabī provides\nan extensive description of the contrast between those who\nsee with the eye of intellectual discrimination and those who Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 12 13 see with both eyes."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "He calls this chapter ‘On Recognizing the\nAlchemy of Felicity.’ ‘Felicity’ is the term used by philosophers\nto translate the Greek work eudaimonia – the happiness that is\nto be attained by the seeker of wisdom."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "It is also astandard term\nfor salvation in Islamic theology, because of a Qurʾanic verse\nsaying that at the resurrection, people will be divided into two\ngroups, the felicitous and the wretched (11:105)."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "And of course,\nAlchemy of Felicity is also the name of al-Ghazālī’s Persian summary of his Ihyāʾ, whether or not Ibn al-ʿArabī was aware of the\nbook’sexistence."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Chapter 167 provides along account of aphilosopher and a\nfollower of the Prophet who set out together to climb the ladder of the cosmos to God."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Just as the celestial spheres represent\nthe descending stages of manifestation and devolution, so also\nthey represent the ascending steps of re-absorption and evolution, steps that one must take if one is to achieve perfection."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The route followed by the two companions goes up through\nthe seven spheres toward the divine presence."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "When the two\nreach the sphere of the moon, the philosopher is granted an\nunderstanding of the moon’sreal nature by the moon’sown\n‘spirituality’ (rūhāniyya), that is, the intelligible, living, spiritual\nreality that the visible moon represents."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In contrast, the follower is introduced to Adam, the prophet whom Muhammad\nmet in the sphere of the moon during his ascent."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Thus the philosopher comes to understand the function of the moon in relation to the entire cosmos, but the follower achieves realization\nof the diverse forms of knowledge actualized by Adam when he\nwas taught the names of all things."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The philosopher, in other\nwords, sees the irst heaven in terms of the eye of intellect, and\nthe follower sees the irst heaven in terms of both eyes – intellect and illumined imagination."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "At each level of ascent through the spheres, the two companions meet similar scenes – the philosopher is presented with the\ndry bones of abstract, rational understanding, and the follower\nis opened up to the lesh and blood of the imaginal realm."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The\nphilosopher remains tied back by his intellect (the word ʿaql\ncomes from the same root as ʿiqāl, fetter), and the follower is\nopened up to multiple dimensions of the divine self-disclosure Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 Ibn al-ʿArabī William C."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Once\nthe two inish traversing the seven spheres, the philosopher is\nheld back from ascending any farther, for intellect, despite its\nability to see into the spiritual realms and to grasp tawhīd, has\nmany limitations."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The eye of imagination, however, is receptive\nto realities far outside the scope of intellect, for, as Ibn al-ʿArabī\nexplains, it opens up to the external World of Imagination itself,\nthe only realm of reality that embraces everything other than\nGod.12\nIbn al-ʿArabī’schapter is clearly addressed to an audience\nfamiliar with the philosophical quest to transcend human limitations and achieve union with the Agent Intellect."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "His purpose\nwas to show that true recognition of self and God, full realization of the human state, will be found only by following in the\nfootsteps of the guides sent by the Real."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In other words it is not\nsuficient to know and realize the reality of the knowledge designated by the formula of tawhīd, ‘There is no god but God,’ as\nthe philosophers do in their quest, even if this knowledge does\nguarantee salvation."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "To achieve the fullness of the human image\nof the divine – the status of the perfect human being, standing\nin the Muhammadan Station – one must also realize the knowledge embraced by the second formula of faith, ‘Muhammad\nis God’s Messenger.’ It is this knowledge alone that opens up\ntrue insight into the World of Nondelimited Imagination, that\nis, everything other than God, an ‘everything’ that has been\nencapsulated by the human reality ever since God taught Adam\nall the names."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In another account of the ascent to God, Ibn al-ʿArabī tells\nthe story in the irst person."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Here he suggests with abit more\nclarity that achieving perfection demands realizing the Real in\nthe full expanse of His self-disclosure within one’svery wujūd,\none’sexistence/inding."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "After spending afew pages describing\nthe stages of his own climb in Muhammad’sfootsteps, he concludes with these words: 12."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "On imagination and the two eyes, see Chittick, Sui Path of Knowledge, especially Chaps. 7 and 20."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 14 Ibn al-ʿArabī 15 This last sentence can stand for the entire contents of The\nMeccan Openings, Ibn al-ʿArabī’sgrand catalogue of the doorways to the Real: ‘Ihave provided no indications of anything\nbut myself.’ The self in question is the human essence, created\nin the image of God and receptive to every name taught by the\nDivine Teacher."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Recognizing this self to whatever extent one is\nable to do so brings forth intimations of the life of the heart."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Such recognition will never be found by blindly imitating\njurists and theologians, not to speak of the thinkers and dreamers of our own times."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Continued from the source text..."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Journal of the Muhyiddin Ibn 'Arabi Society, Vol. 59, 2016 In this journey Igained the meanings of all the divine names."
      }
