      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "The word 'imaginary' is wrecked. Centuries of misuse have pinned it to the floor: unreal, made-up, fantasy. But the Persian and Arabic texts Corbin translates describe something else entirely. Something you can visit. With geography. With inhabitants. Aword still intact, still fit for its purpose."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "In offering the two Latin words mundus imaginalis as the title of this discussion, Iintend to treat aprecise order of reality corresponding to aprecise mode of perception, because Latin terminology gives the advantage of providing us with atechnical and fixed point of reference, to which we can compare the various more-or-less irresolute equivalents that our modern Western languages suggest to us. Iwill make an immediate admission. The choice of these two words was imposed upon me some time ago, because it was impossible for me, in what Ihad to translate or say, to be satisfied with the word imaginary. Regardless of our efforts, we cannot prevent the term imaginary, in current usage that is not deliberate, from being equivalent to signifying unreal, something that is and remains outside of being and existence, something utopian."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "The Latin 'imago' yields 'imaginal' — athird thing between imaginary and intellectual. Areal image that occupies its own order of reality. The Islamic theosophers call it the 'eighth climate.' Seven climate zones for the physical world, and then an eighth beyond geography. Ontological. Amode of reality before which maps fall silent. The word exists because the language needed it."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "If we usually speak of the imaginary as the unreal, the utopian, this must contain the symptom of something. In contrast to this something, we may examine the order of reality that Idesignate as mundus imaginalis, and what our theosophers in Islam designate as the 'eighth climate'; we will then examine the organ that perceives this reality, namely, the imaginative consciousness, the cognitive Imagination; and finally, we will present several examples that suggest to us the topography of these interworlds, as they have been seen by those who actually have been there."
      },
      {
        "kind": "art",
        "art_id": "art_merkaba",
        "caption": "Ezekiel's vision of the Merkaba — an imaginal theophany."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Aword coined by the Persian philosopher Sohravardi: Na-koja-Abad. The land of No-where. It sounds like utopia — same joke, same shape. But utopia is afantasy; Na-koja-Abad has geography."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Let us take the very beautiful tales, simultaneously visionary tales and tales of spiritual initiation, composed in Persian by Sohravardi. Each time, the visionary finds himself torn away from the geographical earth that he knows, and he enters into arelationship with amysterious being who appears to him, abeing who is the Perfect Nature, the active Intelligence, the Guardian Angel of humanity. The itinerary of this visionary geography reveals aregion that does not appear on any map of the physical world, yet is not afiction. Na-koja-Abad is astrange term. It does not occur in any Persian dictionary. It was coined by Sohravardi himself. Literally, it signifies the city, the country or land of No-where. It may appear as the exact equivalent of the term utopia, and yet with regard to the concept, the intention, and the true meaning, Ibelieve that we would be guilty of mistranslation."
      },
      {
        "kind": "art",
        "art_id": "art_sufi_dancer",
        "caption": "Na-koja-Abad: the soul's ecstatic journey beyond physical space."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Na-koja-Abad has extension — real extension, the kind that belongs to cultivated land and cities. It has topography, inhabitants, relations between them. Amap exists for it, just amap of adifferent kind of space. 'Where is it?' gets areal answer: it begins on the convex surface of the Ninth Sphere, the limit of the cosmos, and from there opens into ageography that mirrors the soul'sinterior."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "The word Na-koja-Abad does not designate something like unextended being. The Persian word 'abad' signifies acity, acultivated land, thus something extended. The extension of that land is not of the same order as the extension of aphysical city. But it is an extension. Sohravardi represents the composite of the mystical cities: Jabalqa, Jabarsa, and Hurqalya. Topographically, this region begins on the convex surface of the Ninth Sphere, the Sphere that includes the whole of the cosmos, the limit of physical space. It is amatter of entering, passing into the interior and, paradoxically, finding oneself outside. Henceforth, it is spiritual reality that envelops, surrounds, contains the reality called material. That is why spiritual reality is not in the where. It is the where that is in it."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "This reversal is the eighth climate. Anew dimension that opens when you realize spirit contains matter. To enter it is to pass beyond the mountain of Qaf that rings the physical world. On the other side, distance stops being measured in miles. Two souls side by side in physical space may be worlds apart here. Two souls separated by oceans may be neighbors. Affinity replaces geography."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Let us pause amoment before the topography that Sohravardi describes in the 'Rustling of Gabriel's Wings.' The traveler meets abeing, his Perfect Nature, his Angel. This being tells him: 'If you wish to know the Cities, know that our city, the city of the Angel, lies beyond the mountain of Qaf.' The mountain of Qaf is the cosmic mountain that surrounds the physical world. To pass beyond it is to enter the eighth climate."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "The imaginal world is beyond Qaf. The organ that discerns it is athird faculty, suspended between the physical senses and the pure intellect: the active Imagination."
      },
      {
        "kind": "art",
        "art_id": "art_sun_moon",
        "caption": "The eighth climate: where spiritual reality envelops material."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Our authors distinguish between three universes. First, the sensory world, the world of physical experience. Second, the world of pure Intelligences, the realm of archetypes and angels. And between these two is placed an intermediate world, which our authors designate as 'alam al-mithal, the world of the Image, mundus imaginalis: aworld as ontologically real as the world of the senses and the world of the intellect, aworld that requires afaculty of perception belonging to it. That faculty is the imaginative power, the one we must avoid confusing with the imagination that modern man identifies with fantasy and that produces only the imaginary. The active Imagination is the preeminent mirror, the epiphanic place of the Images of the archetypal world."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "The active Imagination receives. It is amirror. It takes archetypal Images and gives them form so they can be seen — an organ of knowledge in aworld that calls it fantasy. The same substantial reality takes different shapes at each level: pure Intelligence in the intelligible world, Image in the imaginal world, physical object in the sensory world. The Imagination traces that continuity across all three."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "It is afunction that leads us to represent that the same substantial realities assume forms corresponding to each universe. What is apure Intelligence in the intelligible world becomes an Image in the imaginal world and aphysical object in the sensory world. The active Imagination permits rigorous analogical knowledge. It escapes the dualism of matter and spirit, the divorce that has haunted Western philosophy since Descartes. Through the Imagination, we can know the subtle body, the intermediate reality that links the soul to the body. That world is the world of subtle bodies, the idea of which proves indispensable if one wishes to describe alink between the pure spirit and the material body."
      },
      {
        "kind": "art",
        "art_id": "art_conjunction",
        "caption": "The Imagination as mirror of the archetypal world."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Swedenborg arrives as a Western witness, two centuries earlier, on the other side of the world. He described heaven in terms that map exactly onto Na-koja-Abad. Space in heaven corresponds to states of interior. Change of place is change of state. The same principle, arrived at by adifferent route."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Swedenborg explains that all changes of place in the spiritual world are effected by changes of state in the interiors. Spaces in heaven are simply the external conditions corresponding to the internal states. Such adescription is eminently appropriate to Na-koja-Abad and its mysterious Cities. In relation to the corporeal place, the spiritual place is a No-where."
      },
      {
        "kind": "art",
        "art_id": "art_tree_of_life",
        "caption": "Swedenborg's heaven: space as state of interior."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "The distance between two souls in the spiritual world is amatter of difference in inner state — geography has nothing on it. This is why visionary geography holds steady across traditions: the same inner states produce the same landscapes because the imaginal world has stable structures that appear to anyone who reaches the appropriate depth."
      },
      {
        "kind": "ai",
        "text": "Any complete cosmology must account for this intermediate world. The subtle body, the imaginal realm, the active Imagination — these are the missing terms that connect matter to spirit, body to soul. Acosmology that leaves them out is aflat universe where everything is either measurable matter or subjective fantasy. Most people live there. Corbin'swork is the way out."
      },
      {
        "kind": "art",
        "art_id": "art_ouroboros",
        "caption": "The subtle body: the link between spirit and matter."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "We must, at all events, have available acosmology of such akind that the most astounding information of modern science remains inferior to it. This cosmology must account for the subtle body, the idea of which proves indispensable if one wishes to describe alink between the pure spirit and the material body."
      },
      {
        "kind": "source",
        "text": "Such is the constitution of the intermediate world, the mundus imaginalis, the world that is the place of the soul and the place of the subtle body. It is the world where everything that is separated finds its union, where everything that is dispersed finds its gathering. It is the world of the soul'strue country, the homeland to which the mystic returns when he has completed the journey of the outer life."
      }
